''World Snooker'' received average to positive results from critics. [[Computer and Video Games]] magazine scored the game at 72% on both versions.<ref name=CVG/> ''CVG'' praised the game's "brilliant" presentation, that was "bound to appeal to fans of the sport" but criticized the game's high difficulty, but did acknowledge there was "plenty to keep enthusiasts amused for hours on end".<ref name=CVG/>

[[Zzap]] magazine also scored the game highly at 75% when reviewing the Amiga version, saying the game was "a pretty slick snooker sim which is bound to appeal to all Davis fans."<ref name=Zzap/> [[The Games Machine]] rated the game highly at 81% for both versions of the game, saying it was a "must have for mouse-wielding cue freaks."<ref name=GamesM />

[[ACE (games magazine)|Advanced Computing Entertainment]] magazine gave the game, 540/1000<ref name="ACE">{{cite magazine| url=https://archive.org/stream/ace-magazine-21/ACE_Issue_21_1989_Jun#page/n57/mode/1up | title=Steve Davis World Snooker ST Review | author=Jarratt, Steve | magazine=[[ACE (games magazine)|ACE magazine]] | issue=21 | date=June 1989 | page=58 | url-status=live | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160613215521/http://archive.org/stream/ace-magazine-21/ACE_Issue_21_1989_Jun#page/n57/mode/1up | archive-date=June 13, 2016 }}</ref> commenting that while "It's fun to play as a game in its own right, and does have lasting interest, as long as you appreciate its idiosyncrasies", "genuine snooker and pool enthusiasts won't be greatly impressed."<ref name="ACE"/>
